<br>
1. Let's assume guild A is an evil guild, they go by r/p and story.<br>
2. Let's assume guild B is an evil guild, they go by the old alignment structure.<br>
3. Guild A gets a lot of &quot;unkempt druids&quot;, &quot;fallen paladins&quot;, etc. etc. They have to try and figure out which of these applicants is &quot;really evil&quot; depending on how they as a guild define it. (An equivalent good guild would attract a host of &quot;Drizzt&quot; types, necromancers that have forsaken evil but still raise undead, what have you.)<br>
4. Guild B has an easy time with who to recruit, as their structure is black and white. However, they do risk missing out on a genuinely well r/p'd &quot;evil&quot; variation of a &quot;good&quot; race/class/diety combo. These guilds simply assume that they stand to gain a lot more than they lose with this structure.<br>
<br>
Now here's the funny part, guilds A and B seem to often get in a pissing contest over who is &quot;really r/p evil&quot;. Why is this? Each guild provides a home to r/p'ers of different schools. This variety allows players to play, (on the only r/p server in existance), and choose the style of r/p that fits them best. While I personally lean heavily in the Guild-B direction philosophically, I think it's great for folks to have the choice. (My gripe with the non-alignment method is that a lot of guilds who go that route fall into the trap of doing it for effectiveness of class mix more than r/p.)<br>
<br>
I play a light side character. My guild is strict about the old alignment system. We do this because it is logistically workable, and eliminates any graying of our image. I like our ways, but that does not mean other ways cannot be good too. I think that as long as both guilds A and B are doing what they can, to encourage players to breathe some life into their characters, it's all mostly good.<br>
<br>
Cheers,<br>
Beren <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ilharessviviennelileath>Ilharess Vivienne Lileath</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/7/03 3:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=47>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.shaw.ca/baddog117/vivieyes.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Drama</span><hr size=1> Given the nature of our guild, we have to be rather selective of our members ( limited numbers - 15 max, close familial environment, STRICTLY roleplay as we can not be a raiding or loot guild with mostly casters and varying level ranges ).<br>
<br>
Now, I am not sure if this would work for everybody, but it seems to for us. We have a 9 day initiation period ( the number 3 being special number to us ). Any hopeful witch has access to a secured chat channel that we have open and that all tagged members are on. We use this channel for guild talk mostly, instead of /gu. This way, all members can get to know the initiate, and them the members. The initiate won't be able to read the MOTD , but will be informed of any activities we are planning and are more that welcome to attend any rituals or other events that we do.<br>
<br>
Once the 9 day period is up, one of the Inner Circle will ask the guild whether or not to invite the hopeful. If there are no issues with the initiate, there is a short cleansing ritual, and they gain the Daughters Nocturnae tag and their personal title. Essentially, this is just a final step, for if they fit with us, they have already earned their place amongst us in the 9 day period and are treated as a member during that time.<br>
<br>
As I said, it may not work for some others, but it does work for us, just a thought &lt;shrugs&gt; <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.shaw.ca/baddog117/vivirose.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dididaryth>Didi D Aryth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Worshipping Tallonar since 3160</span><br>  Posts: 394<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/7/03 6:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm49.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=31.topic&index=48>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://users.bigpond.net.au/stbt/didi/a_didisig.gif height=120 width=120></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Drama</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Or, how about judge them based on their roleplay ability? And who cares what the hell other guilds think about your decisions? If you invite someone because they are an impeccable roleplayer, then who cares what anyone thinks?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->We DO judge them based on their roleplay ability.  We don't really care what other guilds think of our decisions.  But just because someone is an impeccable roleplayer doesn't mean they fit with the League's goals or perspective.  We choose to be evil, therefore we choose to recruit evil people (who roleplay well).  As soon as we put that decision into place, we now need to define evil for recruitment purposes.<br>
<br>
Beren's examples were good.<br>
<br>
The problem with guild type A as he described it is all the people who 'roleplay' evil.  Everybody has a different idea of what is evil.  For example, is a dwarf who roleplays evil, really evil, even if he hasn't ruined his Kaladim faction?  To answer that we need to make a decision based on the quality of their roleplay.  No two people are going to exactly agree.  It will all come down to your individual experience with the dwarf's roleplay, which will be different for each person who interacts with him by the very nature of roleplay.  I'd be surprised if it was even easy to get a consensus between the officers, let alone the guild.  Some people in the guild may feel that the dwarf isn't truly evil if he can still enter Kaladim.  They'll get upset if he's recruited.  Guild arguments and debates will occur.  Debates on the nature of evil and recruitment policy will follow.  Everybody has a slightly different opinion, so these debates will drag on and on getting people irritated and ruffling feathers till everybody's upset. <br>
<br>
There's only two ways I can see that ending.  (1) the guild is in complete turmoil and tears itself apart over 'how to be evil', or (2) it comes down to 'trust your recruitment officers and shut up' which essentially boils down to 'he's evil if Didi says he's evil'.  Which is still a position I really don't want to be in - and I don't want to see anybody in.<br>
<br>
Nice little theory in an ideal world.  Like I said, maybe even possible in small guilds - like, apparently, the Daughters Nocturnae.  I for one have seen enough to know I don't want any part in trying to make it work for a guild the size of the League.  It's just not realistic without changing to a 'recruitment officer is the ultimate roleplay authority' arrangement, and I could not support that. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><br>
